**Overall meaning:**

"He who knows this thus and meditates upon it, conquers evil deeds in all his life. Thus, he lives long and happily. His enemies do not perish; we enjoy him in this world and in that world. He who knows this thus and meditates upon it."

**Explanation:**

This verse describes the benefits of understanding and meditating on the truth revealed through the fire's teachings.

* **"He who knows this thus and meditates upon it, conquers evil deeds in all his life"**: This emphasizes the transformative power of knowledge and meditation. By understanding the interconnectedness of all things and aligning oneself with the divine, one can overcome negative actions and live a virtuous life.
* **"Thus, he lives long and happily"**: This highlights the positive consequences of a life aligned with divine knowledge and virtue.
* **"His enemies do not perish; we enjoy him in this world and in that world"**: This suggests that the person who embodies this understanding becomes a source of joy and benefit to others, both in this life and the next. They are seen as a force for good that transcends the limitations of the physical world.
* **"He who knows this thus and meditates upon it"**: This repetition emphasizes the importance of ongoing understanding and practice to achieve spiritual liberation.

The verse suggests that by understanding the interconnectedness of the universe and the presence of Brahman within all beings, one can live a life free from negativity, achieve happiness, and become a source of positive influence for others, extending their benefits beyond this life. 




